Yes—an organized factual dossier can be extremely useful. The key is to make it evidence, not a prosecution brief. Let the records show what they show.

For each item, capture:
- the original source and metadata, not just screenshots;
- dates/times and access history;
- what the material contained;
- whether it was actually confidential and not publicly disclosed;
- the engineer’s role and level of access;
- a side-by-side comparison of your nonpublic design decisions with their released behavior.

A clean chronology will help most: internal discussion/design → his access or downloads → resignation/onboarding timing → competitor launch. Flag suspicious facts, but label assumptions as assumptions. “Viewed architecture diagram on [date]” is strong; “therefore exported it” is a hypothesis unless logs support it.

One caution: preserve Slack and other company data through your normal authorized processes, with counsel guiding scope. Don’t rummage through personal accounts, devices, or anything you don’t clearly own or have authority to access. And keep the circle tight—no internal venting or speculative messages that could later be discoverable.

You’re doing the right thing by channeling the anger into a disciplined record. The best outcome isn’t just having “ammo”; it’s giving counsel enough clean evidence to choose the right escalation confidently.
